images.title: Recent Post Had This Image
images.description:
Recently @153armstrong made a post about engine types (neat if you haven't seen it), and the final image was of this description of a jet engine.  It was difficult not to comment, and a fellow imgurian agreed that I should make a more informative post.

I'm sorry if this is an information overload, but I've spent a lot of time doing calculations for these things, and I'll be damned if I can't share it!

images.title: Correct Diagram
images.description:
This is a diagram of the most basic jet engine that's in production today: specifically an axial turbojet.  It has all the required stages to keep working, but no extras (we'll get to those below...SO FUN!)

I'll be going over each part in the next four pictures, and explaining what they do and how they work.

images.title: Compressor Stages!
images.description:
I know it's not a jet engine, but large compressors for power plants and such are so much more fun to look at.

The compressor takes ambient temperature/pressure air and raises the temperature and pressure of it.  It does so by forcing the air through smaller and smaller width channels (check picture 2 where the arrows go into the narrower passages).  The higher the pressure in the next step, the better, so compressors have gotten more intense over the past few decades, and people spend entire careers perfecting the programs that model compressor blade angles.
